496
54:27.540 --> 54:31.986
or in other words, we
can run it in reverse.

497
54:31.986 --> 54:38.520
To illustrate how this works, let's imagine that we first run R and then we run R in reverse,

498
54:38.520 --> 54:42.180
which we can express as R dagger.

499
54:42.180 --> 54:52.110
To be clear about this, what it means is that we apply the gates
of R in the reverse order and we take the inverses
of each of the gates.

500
54:52.110 --> 54:58.890
NOT gates, controlled NOT
gates and Toffoli gates are actually their own inverses, so if we're thinking in
terms of these gates,

501
54:58.890 --> 55:03.810
then R dagger is really just R with the gates supplied
in the reverse order.

502
55:03.810 --> 55:10.020
But in general, we can always run any unitary quantum circuit in reverse in the manner that I just described,

503
55:10.020 --> 55:17.970
meaning that we apply the
gates in the reverse order and we replace each of the
individual gates by its inverse.

504
55:17.970 --> 55:24.390
If we were to do this, we'd find that first running R and then running R in
reverse does nothing at all.

505
55:24.390 --> 55:33.630
So if we started out in a standard basis state like we have here, then we would end in exactly the same standard basis state.

506
55:33.630 --> 55:41.460
Of course, doing just
that isn't very helpful, but what we can do is we can introduce a bunch of extra qubits and specifically,

507
55:41.460 --> 55:47.970
this is M qubits where M is the number of output bits of the circuit C.

508
55:47.970 --> 55:55.080
These additional qubits could
be in any quantum state, but to explain how this works, we're going to assume that they're in a standard basis state

509
55:55.080 --> 56:02.580
corresponding to some string Y. So Y is an M-bit string, and what we can do is to perform

510
56:02.580 --> 56:09.240
a bunch of controlled NOT
gates like you see right here, which effectively XORs the string F of X

511
56:09.240 --> 56:12.720
onto the string Y stored
in these bottom M qubits.

512
56:12.720 --> 56:18.900
And so the output of
the entire computation is as it appears on the screen.

513
56:18.900 --> 56:28.230
X and Y are arbitrary binary strings. X has M-bits and Y has M-bits, and we also need K workspace qubits.

514
56:28.230 --> 56:36.300
When we run R, we compute F of X and that string is stored
in the top M qubits, but we also have a
bunch of garbage qubits,

515
56:36.300 --> 56:44.910
so we XOR the output F of
X onto the bottom M qubits and then run R in reverse
to clean up the garbage.

516
56:44.910 --> 56:48.750
I should point out that it's important that R is deterministic.

517
56:48.750 --> 56:55.440
If these top M qubits could be instead in some superposition of
standard base of stats, this wouldn't work correctly,

518
56:55.440 --> 56:59.100
but this does work when
R is deterministic.

519
56:59.100 --> 57:07.800
So if we compare the quantum
circuit we just built to the original Boolean circuit C, we see that it basically
works in the same way

520
57:07.800 --> 57:12.480
that a query gate works
for an arbitrary function.

521
57:12.480 --> 57:20.340
There is a difference here, which is that we need
these workspace qubits to make it all work, but otherwise we've
effectively built a query gate

522
57:20.340 --> 57:25.680
or a query circuit for whatever function it is that C computes.

523
57:25.680 --> 57:32.220
We also managed, by the way, to return the workspace
qubits to their initial state, so they could in principle be reused

524
57:32.220 --> 57:38.010
as workspace qubits for
subsequent computations.

525
57:38.010 --> 57:47.280
If we want to, we can put a box around the entire quantum circuit and call it Q and the relationship to
C becomes more clear.

526
57:47.280 --> 57:53.637
The circuit Q will be
bigger than C in general. We need a handful of quantum
gates in Q for each gate of C,

527
57:53.637 --> 58:01.530
and we also need the controlled
NOT gates in the middle, but the number is still
linear in the size of C.

528
58:01.530 --> 58:10.710
It should also be noted that this is a completely general procedure which works for any Boolean circuit, and we haven't tried at all to optimize Q.

529
58:10.710 --> 58:17.040
For a specific circuit C, there might very well be
ways to reduce the size of Q, and that includes using methods

530
58:17.040 --> 58:24.180
that reduce the number of
workspace qubits needed in case that's something
that we want to do, and that is the procedure for running

531
58:24.180 --> 58:27.750
classical computations
on a quantum computer.

532
58:27.750 --> 58:32.850
It's pretty simple, but it's an important
thing to be able to do.

533
58:32.850 --> 58:38.850
In particular, now that
we know how to do this, we are free to make use of any classical computations we want

534
58:38.850 --> 58:48.090
inside of quantum computations, provided that we follow this form where the input gets echoed and the output gets XORed
onto a bunch of qubits

535
58:48.090 --> 58:51.540
just like we had for query gates.

536
58:51.540 --> 58:59.010
The cost scales linearly. So for example, we can
create quantum circuits for problems like integer addition,

537
58:59.010 --> 59:09.330
multiplication, division, computing GCDs and modular exponentiation, and this can all be done at the same asymptotic cost
as for Boolean circuits.

538
59:09.330 --> 59:15.540
We do need workspace qubits to do this, but at least they're available to be reused again when
we're done with them.

539
59:15.540 --> 59:21.810
One final remark that's worth mentioning is that this method provides us with a method to implement query gates,

540
59:21.810 --> 59:24.990
which I alluded to in the previous lesson.

541
59:24.990 --> 59:33.720
That is, if we have a query algorithm that takes some function F as input, and we have a way to compute
F with a Boolean circuit,

542
59:33.720 --> 59:40.650
then we can follow this procedure to build a query gate for that function and then run our query algorithm on it.

543
59:40.650 --> 59:49.110
Whether or not that's a useful thing to do depends on the query problem itself and what we're trying to accomplish, but in essence, this
construction provides us

544
59:49.110 --> 59:54.120
with a way of connecting the query model to a more standard model of computation.

545
59:54.120 --> 59:59.340
This is in some sense how Shor's algorithm for integer factorization works.

